abstract: >
  Empirical study of LoRA fine-tuning a 12-billion-parameter
  image generation model (Krea 2, a Qwen-Image-family MMDiT)
  to reproduce an original character ("Masafee", a red panda)
  on a single consumer GPU (NVIDIA GeForce RTX 3060 12GB) — a
  model whose half-precision weights (~24GB) do not fit on the
  GPU. Feasibility is achieved by jointly using FP8 scaled
  quantization, block swapping (26 blocks), and PyTorch
  expandable_segments. The LoRA is trained on the
  pre-distillation RAW model and transfers cleanly to 8-step
  Turbo inference. A key finding is that overfitting is
  frequency-asymmetric: high-frequency details (eye
  catchlights) erode before the low-frequency overall form,
  and the degradation is reversibly recovered at inference via
  LoRA strength and text conditioning. The successor to a
  prior Stable Diffusion 1.5 study of the same character.
  Paper (JA/EN), training scripts, dataset, inference
  workflow, and provenance logs are included; LoRA weights
  are distributed on Hugging Face.
